Still by the book, and my bishop on e7 has zero  moves, but at least the same is true for the white bishop on c1. My pawns are advanced, which seems like it should impart mobility to my pieces, and I'm ostensibly ahead in development, though I don't know if I should count my paralyzed bishop on e7, and my knight on the edge at a5 is fairly limited too. What I don't like is my backward pawn at d6, or the hole in my formation at d5.

I'm not sure why I played 12. ... Bd7. Unlike my 5th move 5. ... Be7 which was in my Ruy Lopez reference, even though the reasoning behind it eludes me somewhat, this 12th move deviates from my opening repertoire, I have no reference that suggests this move (Nc6, Rd8, and cxd4 were all suggested), and it doesn't seem to be accomplishing much. I played the move nearly a month ago and don't, now, recall why. Maybe all I wanted to do was break out of prepared, memorized opening moves.

I could not have played 26. ... Nxe4 to equalize material, for then white would play 27. Qxf7  and I would be undone: 27. ... Kh8, 28. Ng6  Kh7, 29. Nxe7 and now I'm down a bishop and pawn, and facing 30. Qg8#.

Starting to feel the stirrings of a draw coming on here. I'm thinking that if white wants to keep his centrally located bishop, he might recapture with 30. fxg3, damaging his pawn structure a little. If he does, I may fight on a bit to see if I can exploit it.

At this point, I offered my opponent a draw. Identical pawn structure, no passed or half-passed pawns, and opposite-colored bishops. Neither side has any exploitable weakness, and our queens are going to have too much defensive scope for our opponent to snatch up a pawn. My opponent accepted. I guess this was good for me, as he was rated 62 points higher than I am, so it's a tiny victory, of a sort.
